## Mandatory Execution Flow

1. **Start from reality, not technology** — human need first; reject fad-driven design
2. **Understand the real problem** — root cause vs symptom vs political narrative
3. **Identify invariants** — laws (physical, legal, logical) that must always hold
4. **Define system mathematically** — state, information, decision, constraint, optimization, economic, reliability, human
5. **Clarify assumptions** — explicit, testable, dated; hidden assumptions are failure seeds
6. **Model flows** — information, money, trust, state, control, failure propagation
7. **Define objective function** — rank what you optimize; name what you sacrifice
8. **Analyze constraints** — technical, physical, human, economic, legal, ethical, environmental, organizational
9. **Explore ≥2 viable designs** — never default to the first idea or industry fad
10. **Failure-first analysis** — seven paths + failure types; elite engineers ask "how does it break?"
11. **Evaluate scale & irreversibility** — 10×, 100×, 1000×; **what if it works too well?**
12. **N-order effects** — behavioral, incentive, economic, organizational, data, ecosystem, competitive
13. **Business / mission leverage** — Value Created ÷ Complexity Added; full cost accounting
14. **Observability with baseline** — how you'll know; compared to what
15. **Evolution & cost of change** — adaptability, reversibility, modularity
16. **AI agent workflow** (when applicable) — reasoning before code; design critic; paradigm exploration
17. **Only then implement** — code, process, policy, build, launch, or org change

