## Phase 2: First-Principles Reasoning

### Define the system mathematically

Before implementation, classify what you're building. Every system is one or more of:

| System type | Core question |
|---|---|
| **State system** | What changes over time? Where is truth? |
| **Information system** | What information flows where? Who consumes it? |
| **Decision system** | What chooses actions? On what inputs? |
| **Constraint system** | What limits behavior? Hard vs soft? |
| **Optimization system** | What are we maximizing? What are we sacrificing? |
| **Economic system** | Who pays cost? Who captures value? |
| **Reliability system** | What happens when parts fail? |
| **Human system** | How do humans misuse, game, or misunderstand it? |

This is how principal engineers think — map all types that apply, then design.

### Invariants (must never break)

An **invariant** is a thing that remains true regardless of implementation. Identify these correctly and frameworks become secondary, architectures adaptable.

State invariants as **testable claims**. Domain examples:

| Domain | Invariant examples |
|---|---|
| **Payments / money** | Conservation; no double spend; auditable trail; **trust required** |
| **Search / discovery** | **Relevance** to intent; explainability where required |
| **Collaboration** | **Synchronization** of shared truth; conflict rules explicit |
| **AI assistants** | **Confidence calibration**; ground truth separated from generation |
| **Social / community** | **Identity + feedback loops**; abuse bounded |
| **Safety** | Interlocks cannot be bypassed without logged override; fail-safe defaults |
| **Auth / access** | Unauthenticated ≠ authorized; least privilege |
| **Inventory** | Reserved ≤ on-hand (unless explicit oversell policy); traceability for recalls |
| **Clinical** | Do-no-harm guardrails; scope of practice enforced |
| **Legal / records** | Retention and immutability rules honored; chain of custody |
| **Environment** | Emissions/discharge within permit; spill containment |
| **AI / automation** | High-impact irreversible actions require policy gate + human where required |
| **Equity** | Protected classes not systematically disadvantaged by rules or models |

### System primitives template (fill for non-trivial work)

| Primitive | Describe for THIS system |
|---|---|
| **Inputs** | Raw materials, requests, tickets, sensor readings, applications, capital |
| **Outputs** | Products, decisions, shipments, diagnoses, reports, experiences |
| **State (stocks)** | Inventory, backlog, cash, reputation, data, WIP, trust |
| **Flows (rates)** | Throughput, hiring, churn, defect rate, cash burn, lead conversion |
| **Transformations** | Manufacturing step, algorithm, review, approval, assembly, fermentation |
| **Decisions / control** | Accept/reject, route, price, escalate, retry, shut down line |
| **Delays** | Shipping time, approval latency, sensor lag, payment settlement, learning curve |
| **Feedback loops** | Quality → returns → cost → corner-cutting (+ vicious); training → fewer errors (− balancing) |
| **Externalities** | Pollution, noise, privacy loss, community impact, vendor dependency |

### Model as flows (if you cannot draw it, you do not understand it)

Everything is flow. Map explicitly:

| Flow type | What to trace |
|---|---|
| **Information flow** | Producers, consumers, transforms, staleness, trust |
| **Money flow** | Who pays, when, reconciliation, leakage |
| **Trust flow** | How trust is earned, lost, delegated, verified |
| **State flow** | Stocks, transitions, consistency boundaries |
| **Control flow** | Decisions, gates, escalations, overrides |
| **Failure propagation** | How one failure cascades across components |

Template: **Inputs → Transformations → Decisions → Outputs → Feedback loops**

### Objective function (explicit priority stack)

Every system optimizes something **implicitly** if you don't define it explicitly — and accidental metrics destroy systems.

**Possible optimization targets (rank, don't hide):**
Revenue · Retention · Trust · Accuracy · Latency · Reliability · Cognitive simplicity · Developer productivity · User success rate · Time-to-value · Network effects · Safety · Compliance · Margin

**When tradeoffs conflict, state your ranking.** Examples — pick or adapt:

| Stack | Priority order |
|---|---|
| **Safety-critical** | human life > regulatory compliance > uptime > cost > speed |
| **Financial core** | correctness > fraud prevention > availability > latency > feature velocity |
| **Consumer growth (early)** | learning speed > margin > perfection > scale efficiency |
| **Enterprise B2B** | reliability > security > integrability > cost > novelty |
| **Research** | validity > reproducibility > novelty > throughput |
| **Sustainability-led** | long-term footprint > short-term margin > convenience |

**Goodhart's law — implicit optimization disasters:**

| If you optimize… | You may get… |
|---|---|
| Engagement (social) | Addiction, outrage, doom-scrolling |
| Clicks (recommendations) | Rage bait, clickbait, misinformation |
| Code generation speed (AI copilots) | Bad architecture, skipped understanding, review theater |
| Growth at all costs (SaaS) | Bad-fit customers, support nightmares, churn bombs |
| Local team velocity | Global complexity, integration debt |

**No ranking = hidden ranking.** Hidden ranking = surprises in production, in court, or in the news.

