## Phase 3: Constraint Analysis

> **Innovation is usually discovering hidden constraints others ignored.**

The best design is rarely the most elegant. It is the one that **survives real-world constraints**.

### Constraint dimensions (scan all)

| Dimension | Ask | Examples |
|---|---|---|
| **Physical** | Mass, energy, space, temperature, materials? | Floor load, battery, cold chain |
| **Technical** | Latency, throughput, precision, compatibility, concurrency, distributed consistency, bandwidth, model context limits, token cost, GPU availability? | p99, MTBF, API version |
| **Temporal** | Deadlines, seasonality, half-life of data? | Tax day, harvest, flash sale |
| **Economic** | CapEx, OpEx, unit economics, working capital? | Margin floor, payback period |
| **Human** | Attention span, onboarding friction, cognitive overload, habit formation, trust, fear of automation, skills, shift length? | Training time, error rate under fatigue |
| **Legal / regulatory** | Statute, contract, license, export control? | GDPR, FDA, SOX, PCI |
| **Ethical / equity** | Who is excluded? Dignity? Consent? | Surveillance, bias, coercion |
| **Environmental** | Emissions, waste, water, biodiversity? | Scope 1–3 targets |
| **Organizational** | Ownership, politics, vendor relationships? | Union rules, matrix org |
| **Cultural / reputational** | Brand, community norms, trust? | "Creepy" feature, greenwashing risk |

### Constraint-driven design patterns (domain-neutral)

* **Hard budget** → simplify scope; buy vs build; reuse; phased delivery
* **Strict audit** → append-only evidence; separation of duties; immutable logs
* **Scarce expertise** → standardize; automate toil; document runbooks; reduce bus factor
* **Geographic dispersion** → regional autonomy with global invariants; async handoffs
* **Low trust environment** → verify, don't assume; dual control; cryptographic or procedural proof
* **High uncertainty** → optionality; modular pieces; reversible pilots; kill criteria

