## Phase 4: Design Exploration (Architecture Alternatives)

Always compare **≥2 viable approaches**. Document **why the loser lost** against your objective function.

### Universal design pattern catalog

Patterns below apply to **software, orgs, supply chains, and policies** — translate the metaphor deliberately.

| Pattern | Good when | Avoid when |
|---|---|---|
| **Centralized control** | Strong consistency; clear accountability; small scale | Bottleneck; local context varies wildly |
| **Federated / regional autonomy** | Local optimization matters; latency to decision | Inconsistent standards; reconciliation pain |
| **Hub-and-spoke** | Economies of scale at hub; predictable routes | Hub failure = systemic; long spokes |
| **Mesh / peer-to-peer** | Resilience; no single point of failure | Coordination cost; harder observability |
| **Modular monolith** | Clear seams; single deploy; future split | Boundaries not enforced |
| **Pipeline / assembly line** | Stable steps; high volume | High variability jobs; frequent rework |
| **Cellular / micro-factory** | Product mix variety | Duplicate overhead |
| **Pull (kanban / JIT)** | Reduce WIP; demand signal clear | Supplier unreliable; long lead times |
| **Push (forecast-driven)** | Stable demand; scale manufacturing | Bullwhip; obsolescence |
| **Buffer / inventory / slack** | Variability absorption | Carrying cost; spoilage; stale data |
| **Synchronized (just-in-time)** | Cost minimization | Any shock breaks system |
| **Redundancy (N+1, hot standby)** | Uptime critical | Cost; complexity; split-brain if wrong |
| **Diversity (dissimilar redundancy)** | Common-mode failure risk | Higher integration cost |
| **Standardization** | Interop; training; quality | Stifles edge cases; slow adaptation |
| **Customization / configure-to-order** | Premium segment | Operational complexity |
| **Outsource / managed service** | Not core competency | Vendor lock; opacity |
| **Insource** | Strategic control; IP | Headcount; capex |
| **Gate / inspection point** | Quality or safety critical | Throughput bottleneck if overused |
| **Fail-fast (stop the line)** | Defect cost >> delay cost | When partial progress still valuable |
| **Graceful degradation** | Partial value beats total failure | Masking serious underlying issues |
| **Strangler / phased migration** | Legacy replacement | Dual-run period complexity |
| **Pilot / RCT / A/B** | Complex or human behavior uncertain | Ethical limits; insufficient power |
| **Deterministic core + AI assist** | AI proposes; rules enforce | AI owns irreversible high-stakes decisions |

### Comparison template (use in reasoning)

| Criterion (weighted) | Option A | Option B | Option C |
|---|---|---|---|
| Meets invariants? | | | |
| Complexity added | | | |
| Reversibility | | | |
| Time to value | | | |
| Operating burden | | | |
| Failure blast radius | | | |
| 10× scale behavior | | | |
| **Weighted score / judgment** | | | |

### Cross-domain comparison examples

**Notifications (digital):** sync in request vs outbox+worker vs managed queue — pick on reliability vs latency stack.

**Staffing (org):** centralized scheduling vs regional autonomy — pick on SLA variance vs coordination cost.

**Quality (manufacturing):** end-of-line inspection vs in-process statistical control — pick on defect escape cost vs capex.

**Moderation (content):** pre-publish human review vs post-publish ML flag — pick on harm velocity vs throughput.

**Pricing (market):** fixed tiers vs usage-based vs outcome-based — pick on predictability vs alignment vs gaming surface.

