## Phase 6: N-Order Effects

| Order | Question | Cross-domain examples |
|---|---|---|
| **1st** | Immediate visible effect? | Faster checkout; cheaper unit cost; fewer support tickets |
| **2nd** | How do agents adapt? | Staff skip safety steps to hit quota; users share workarounds; competitors match price |
| **3rd** | Systemic distortion? | Quality reputation drop; regulatory scrutiny; ecosystem dependency |
| **4th** | Strategic / structural shift? | Platform lock-in; industry consolidation; norm change (privacy expectations) |

### Worked example — AI code autocomplete (1st through 4th order)

| Order | Effect |
|---|---|
| **1st** | Users write code faster |
| **2nd** | Users stop understanding code deeply; technical debt rises; review quality drops; juniors learn less; architecture consistency degrades |
| **3rd** | Org becomes dependent on AI; expertise concentration weakens; bugs become systemic; mediocre engineers appear productive |
| **4th** | Competitive differentiation from speed disappears; **quality and trust become the premium differentiator** |

Use this depth for any high-impact automation or acceleration feature.

### Universal second-order checklist

Whenever adding a feature, ask:

| Lens | Question |
|---|---|
| **Behavioral** | How does user/operator behavior change? |
| **Incentive** | What gets rewarded unintentionally? |
| **Scaling** | What new bottlenecks emerge? |
| **Economic** | Does marginal cost rise or fall? Support burden? |
| **Organizational** | Does maintenance complexity increase? Who owns it? |
| **Data** | Does feedback/data quality improve or decay? |
| **Ecosystem** | Does this weaken or strengthen integration flexibility? |
| **Competitive** | Can competitors copy this easily? Does it erode moat? |

**Mandatory questions:**
* *What happens if this succeeds massively?*
* ***What if it works too well?*** — reveals hidden scaling problems, abuse vectors, governance issues, operational nightmares, societal impacts, economic distortions

| Success scenario | Often neglected failure |
|---|---|
| Viral adoption | Support, fraud, infra, moderation, supply |
| Cost cutting wins awards | Hidden technical debt; safety culture erosion |
| Automation "works" | Skill atrophy; cannot operate manually in crisis |
| Data collection grows | Privacy backlash; breach blast radius |
| Central vendor wins | Negotiating power flips; exit cost |

**Cobra effect reminder:** incentives can **worsen** the original problem. Always ask what behavior you're accidentally paying for.

