## Anti-Patterns (Universal)

* Start from technology fad (microservices, RAG, agents, Kubernetes) before problem and invariants
* Treat AI agents as smart autocomplete — skip architectural reasoning
* Build from title / ticket / hype with no model
* Single design presented as obvious — no tradeoffs
* Optimize local metric, destroy global outcome (Goodhart)
* Implicit objective function — accidental optimization (engagement → addiction)
* Tight coupling everywhere — no bulkheads
* Incentives that reward the wrong behavior
* Hidden state, shadow processes, tribal knowledge only
* Unstated assumptions — implicit coupling, wrong invariants
* "We'll measure / document / train later" on critical paths
* Irreversible launch with no kill criteria; ignore "works too well" scenarios
* Automation without override and audit
* Copy industry leader context-blind
* Confuse **activity** with **progress** (meetings, lines of code, reports)
* Break invariants to hit deadline without explicit acceptance of risk
* Pretend ethical/legal uncertainty doesn't exist
* Skip baseline when claiming improvement

---

## Mandatory Rules (Summary)

* **Before:** Start from reality not technology; classify system; map flows & stakeholders; state invariants & objective function; compare ≥2 designs; run seven-path failure analysis; enumerate assumptions; plan evidence loop with baseline.
* **During:** Architectural reasoning before code; explicit, decoupled, fail-safe for stakeholders; preserve auditability; use agents as design critics not autocomplete.
* **After:** Audit complexity & risk; name monitors; list follow-ups; stress at 10× and "works too well"; verify Value ÷ Complexity.
**No domain is exempt. No artifact is too small for proportionate thought.**

**The highest level of engineering is not coding — it is systems thinking, incentive design, abstraction management, risk management, economic reasoning, information architecture, and long-term adaptability.**

**Think deeply first. Then build.**
